\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{pgfplots}
\pgfplotsset{compat=1.17}
\usepgfplotslibrary{fillbetween}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}
    \begin{axis}[
        title={R-IGD},
        xlabel={$\gamma$},
        ylabel={R-IGD},
        xmode=log,
        legend pos=north west,
        grid=both,
    ]

    % R-IGD(pop)
    \addplot[
        blue,
        mark=x,
        smooth,
        error bars/.cd,
        y dir=both,
        y explicit,
    ] 
    coordinates {
        (1e-4, 0.1) ± (0, 0.02)
        (1e-3, 0.11) ± (0, 0.015)
        (5e-2, 0.12) ± (0, 0.03)
        (1e+00, 0.18) ± (0, 0.04)
    };
    \addplot[
        blue,
        name path=upper_blue,
        draw=none,
        mark=none,
    ] coordinates {
        (1e-4, 0.12) (1e-3, 0.125) (5e-2, 0.15) (1e+00, 0.22)
    };
    \addplot[
        blue,
        name path=lower_blue,
        draw=none,
        mark=none,
    ] coordinates {
        (1e-4, 0.08) (1e-3, 0.095) (5e-2, 0.09) (1e+00, 0.14)
    };
    \addplot[blue!20, fill opacity=0.5] fill between[of=upper_blue and lower_blue];

    % R-IGD(pred)
    \addplot[
        orange,
        mark=triangle,
        smooth,
        error bars/.cd,
        y dir=both,
        y explicit,
    ]
    coordinates {
        (1e-4, 0.1) ± (0, 0.01)
        (1e-3, 0.11) ± (0, 0.01)
        (5e-2, 0.13) ± (0, 0.02)
        (1e+00, 0.29) ± (0, 0.05)
    };
    \addplot[
        orange,
        name path=upper_orange,
        draw=none,
        mark=none,
    ] coordinates {
        (1e-4, 0.11) (1e-3, 0.12) (5e-2, 0.15) (1e+00, 0.34)
    };
    \addplot[
        orange,
        name path=lower_orange,
        draw=none,
        mark=none,
    ] coordinates {
        (1e-4, 0.09) (1e-3, 0.10) (5e-2, 0.11) (1e+00, 0.24)
    };
    \addplot[orange!20, fill opacity=0.5] fill between[of=upper_orange and lower_orange];

    \legend{R-IGD(pop), R-IGD(pred)}
    \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

### Explanation:

- **Package Import**: The `pgfplots` package is used for creating high-quality plots. The `fillbetween` library is used to create the shaded regions representing standard deviations.
- **Axis Configuration**: The `xmode=log` option is used to set the x-axis to logarithmic scale.
- **Plotting Data**: The `\addplot` command is used to plot the data points with their respective markers (`x` for `R-IGD(pop)` and `triangle` for `R-IGD(pred)`).
- **Error Bars**: Error bars are added using the `error bars` configuration, though in this specific example, the shaded area approach is used for clarity.
- **Shaded Areas**: The `fill between` library is utilized to create shaded areas representing one standard deviation above and below the mean values.
- **Legend**: The legend is positioned at the north-west corner of the plot.

